body:
I think this should not result in multidriven warning.
Just a linting warning, but still a bug.

```verilog
module test;
    typedef struct {
        logic val1;
        logic val2;
    } str_t;
    str_t str;

    always_comb begin
        str.val1 = 1'b0;
    end

    always_comb begin
        str.val2 = 1'b0;
    end
endmodule
```
Results in:

```
%Warning-MULTIDRIVEN: test.sv:13:9: Variable written to in always_comb also written by other process (IEEE 1800-2017 9.2.2.2): 'str'
                                  : ... In instance test
                      test.sv:13:9:
   13 |         str.val2 = 1'b0;
      |         ^~~
                      test.sv:9:9: ... Location of other write
    9 |         str.val1 = 1'b0;
      |         ^~~
                      ... For warning description see https://verilator.org/warn/MULTIDRIVEN?v=5.011
                      ... Use "/* verilator lint_off MULTIDRIVEN */" and lint_on around source to disable this message.
%Error: Exiting due to 1 warning(s)
```

It does not happen if the struct is packed.

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?
Verilator 5.011 devel rev v5.010-30-g0606a29f1

May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?
Sure
